abstract: WESTCHESTER, Penn., April 9.--A premature explosion of several heavy blasts of giant powder in a rock cutting, where the Pennsylvania Railroad is being straightened, near Downington, occurred last evening. Twenty-five men were immediately in front of the blasts, but most of them escaped fatal injury. John Powers, the overseer, and Robert Taylor, a laborer, were killed, the former being frightfully mangled. Six or eight men were badly hurt, and several more sustained slight wounds.
